{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"00184981-6b8a-47e5-8e51-d3495aa23b57","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, so I'll give you the guidance directly.\n\nTo publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool**, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server over stdio.</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nThen **pack and publish**:\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nUsers install and run it with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs over stdio\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- `PackAsTool` — required; marks the package as a global/local tool.\n- `ToolCommandName` — the CLI command name users will type.\n- `OutputType` must be `Exe` (it already should be for a stdio server).\n- Get an API key from [nuget.org/account/apikeys](https://www.nuget.org/account/apikeys).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"16fcf085-9e4d-4308-a64b-f21af2f738ae","outputTokens":448},"id":"213ba7b0-6eee-4419-85b3-5db24d6ab56c","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:47:36.625Z","parentId":"f26723b6-7572-479a-beca-7f42b659a678"}
